Knives Out is a 2019 dramatic thriller directed by Rian Johnso who You may know from directing such films as Looper and The Last Jedi. The film stars 
Ana de Armas as Marta Cabrera and Daniel Craig as Detective Benoit Blanc.

An extremely entertaining and memorable film that I will certainly be watching again. The cast was fantastic, the characters were incredibly enjoyable, the story was engaging, and for the most part, something we haven't seen before, but the strongest aspect of the film, in my opinion, was definitely the chemistry between the Thrombey family.

Overall I give it an
8/10 - really strong film, would definitely recommend
The ending was completely predictable. Just about all of the characters were silly, exaggerated caricatures. It was like I was watching a bad Chuck Lorre TV show.

Follows in the tradition of tongue-in-cheek whodunnits with large casts (think Clue and Murder on the Orient Express) but is wholly its own unique experience filled with memorable set pieces and laugh out loud moments. This features one of 2019's strongest cast ensembles, with Daniel Craig offering another career high performance.

"Knives Out," a quick-witted murder mystery, moves at high speed from start to finish. After the mysterious death of grandfather Harlan Thrombey (Christopher Plummer), Detective Benoit Blank (Daniel Craig) is on the case to solve exactly what happened as he interacts with the highly dysfunctional and greedy Thrombey Family, unlocking their secrets as he investigates. With the star-studded cast each character manages to be quirkier than the next and though not every character gets their time to shine equally, they still take the spotlight when they have the opportunity. Aside from the characters' secrets, who give this movie its classic murder feel, the set design of the manor was just as mysterious and could have been explored more. However, though "Knives Out" attempts to play as a classic â€˜whodunit' it doesn't successfully use the strong elements it has to reach that point. The pieces are there, but the execution was not done well. The third act is where this movie runs into problems as it takes a long detour from the manor and the characters who we spent time getting to know. But, if you enjoy mysteries, "Knives Out" is worth the watch. It's entertaining, witty, and mysterious.

Amazing cast. Daniel Craig is as good as ever hamming it up. Very interesting way of telling a whodunit and sticks the landing. Great film to see in a filled theater for lots of laughs and twists and turns.
I liked the plot twists in the movie.
